text:
y reminder: im taking you guys back to the beginning of my end💫💫💫💫 #wcw this is not my current state💪🏽 yoga? we can afford everything else. but not yoga? 80 bucks a month.. gtfoh!! i can spend $800 on bs on a whim. that’s ok tho right.... that shit made you look good to the outside world, the world you feverishly tried to deceive. you saw that shit was bringing peace in my life. yoga had to go. you knew peace would soon bring clarity. lifting that heavy fog from my eyes. i could no longer visit the studio as i pleased. it’s all good tho. it made my #yoga practice stronger, self taught. i advanced because i did it “on the side” late night, early morning when you was working 🙃 got @yogaglo for the quick $20 a month. to sum it all up...fuuuuuuuck you!🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️🧘🏽‍♀️do not forget to post yourself today as #wcw in honor of #selflove #metoo #eyeswideopen #eyeseeyou✨💫📿👁🧚🏾‍♂️ 🕉📿🔮☮️ namasteॐ 💫 ✨💫 💫✨ 💫✨

text: just a psa as we start the new year. in regards to sexual assault, no means no. sleeping means no. no answer means no. absolutely, under any circumstance ever is it okay for a woman (or man) to wake up with someone’s hand up her (or his) shirt. that is sexual assault. regardless of whether every other time it’s been yes, this is still sexual assault. replying “it’s just a boob” is not an appropriate response. we need to have more open dialogue about these very real issues that men and women deal with because change will never happen otherwise. i’m sick and tired of worrying about being assaulted by strangers, but it hurts even more when it’s someone you thought was a friend. please, please, please always communicate in these situations and raise awareness so that we can at least stop ignorant sexual assault. featuring a photo of me feeling like a badass to help alleviate my frustration. #metoo

text:
i know, i know. i’ve been super quiet lately! and it kills me inside because this work means the absolute world to me. i found it hard to juggle everything towards the end of last year—especially my ever-growing, non-stop social life. which i know—it’s my own fault!

two days into 2019, i sit here grateful. beyond grateful for all of the opportunities that opened up for me last year, grateful for the hard work that paid off, grateful for the negative things i let go of and grateful for the beautiful things that came into my life.

i’ve said it before and i’ll say it again, 2018 was the best year of my life to date. and if my gut instinct is anything to go by, 2019 is going to be even better! i have big plans for growing my brand and expanding my horizons, and i am so, so excited to see them all come to fruition.

here’s a pic of me bringing in the new year, doing what i do best—looking like a dork, having a boog in the dust x

text:
2018 has been the hardest, and somehow both the longest and the shortest  year of our lives. happy new year and thank you to everyone whose support has pulled us through. the road to justice for gaia will be long but with your continued support we're hoping at least to get some answers and some accountability in 2019. 
on #newyearseve we wrote gaia's name in light up at her favourite pub (and ours) the square and compass in worth matravers. some impromptu #artforgaia courtesy of dom and maya.

text:
::: n e w. y e a r´s. e v e. a n d. a d a m ::: l’année qui s’écoule fut clairement féminine. le féminin s’est affirmé à travers différents mouvements #metoo, l’explosion d’ateliers, conférences, livres autour du féminin sacré, la dénonciation d’actes toujours plus choquants mais aussi les prises de parole pour proposer de nouvelles idées et actions vers plus de paix.
les femmes s’imposent de plus en plus, s’expriment, se défendent, s’autorisent. 
on parlera de féminisme parfois, d’autres fois de « crise identitaire féminine ». mais le féminin ne se trouve pas uniquement chez les femmes. les hommes aussi en sont fait, tout comme les femmes sont faites de masculin. cette année n’a pas simplement mis en lumière une volonté de prouver la place des femmes dans la société ; elle a aussi démontré que les hommes tenaient un rôle déterminant dans ces actions. un rôle à ne pas diminuer car porteur de solidarité, d’implication et de prise de conscience. tous les hommes ne sont pas des porcs à balancer ; très très loin de là. le mouvement féministe est aussi un mouvement masculiniste. en fait, c’est un mouvement d’humains souhaitant rétablir l’équilibre. mon souhait pour cette année 2019 est dans ce sens : l’inclusion. qu’aucune femme et qu’aucun homme ne ressente ses actions diminuées par son genre/sexe. inclure pour aller plus loin ensemble, inclure pour plus d’harmonie et de paix. alors, pour tout ce qui a déjà été entrepris, merci 🙏🏽 merci à toutes les femmes qui ont ouvert cette voie et à tous les hommes qui les ont soutenues au cours de l’année 2018. 
et plus personnellement, une profonde gratitude envers mes lo(u)ves, mes non lo(u)ves, mes o(u)rs & mes non o(u)rs pour votre touchante sensibilité, votre soutien et votre amour tout au long de cette année super difficile... lo(u)ve you ❤️
que cette année 2019 soit portée par le « nous » et la non-dualité ❤️ une surprise pour juin nous attend dans ce sens, en attendant, très belle année à vous, à nous ! 
art : @taylaob.art

text:
si nos sigues en facebook podrás descargar el libro de ana de miguel, "neoliberalismo sexual", el mito de la libre elección @catedraeditorial

la obra versa sobre la ideología neoliberal, que tiene por objetivo "convertir la vida en mercancía, incluso a los seres humanos". en ese sentido, reflexiona sobre "la conversión de los cuerpos de las mujeres en mercancía" como "el medio más eficaz para difundir y reforzar la ideología neoliberal". "la poderosa industria del sexo patriarcal avanza apoyándose en dos ideas complementarias". por un lado, en la teoría de la libre elección: ahora que las mujeres "ya son libres", "ya tienen igualdad", pueden "elegir" vivir de su cuerpo o de trozos de su cuerpo. por otro lado, y para contrarrestar cualquier crítica, esta tesis se envuelve en cierta retórica transgresora y posmoderna: toda relación es aceptable si hay "sexo consentido" por el medio.
.
.
.
.

la obra versa sobre la ideología neoliberal, que tiene por objetivo "conveir la vida en mercancía, incluso a los seres humanos". en ese sentido, reflexiona sobre "la conversión de los cuerpos de las mujeres en mercancía" como "el medio más eficaz para difundir y reforzar la ideología neoliberal". "la poderosa industria del sexo patriarcal avanza apoyándose en dos ideas complementarias". por un lado, en la teoría de la libre elección: ahora que las mujeres "ya son libres", "ya tienen igualdad", pueden "elegir" vivir de su cuerpo o de trozos de su cuerpo. por otro lado, y para contrarrestar cualquier crítica, esta tesis se envuelve en ciea retórica transgresora y posmoderna: toda relación es aceptable si hay "sexo consentido" por el medio.

text:
- she [rebekah mercer] loved me. she was like, oh we need more of your type on our side!

your type? - the gays. she loved the gays. so did steve [bannon]. he saw us as early adopters. he figured, if you can get the gays on board, everyone else will follow. it’s why he was so into the whole milo [yiannopoulos] thing.

robert mercer was a pioneer in ai and machine translation. he helped invent algorithmic trading – which replaced hedge fund managers with computer programs – and he listened to wylie’s pitch. it was for a new kind of political message-targeting based on an influential and groundbreaking 2014 paper researched at cambridge’s psychometrics centre, called: - computer-based personality judgments are more accurate than those made by humans. - in politics, the money man is usually the dumbest person in the room. whereas it’s the opposite way around with mercer, says wylie. - he said very little, but he really listened. he wanted to understand the science. and he wanted proof that it worked.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
that’s what qanon followers really want, after all. that’s where their “storm” motto comes from. most americans were puzzled when, in a meeting with military leaders months ago, trump said, “you know what this represents? maybe it’s the calm before the storm.” but these theorists thought they knew exactly what he was talking about. trump was pointing at the officers’ uniforms.

the storm qanon truthers predict will never strike because the conspiracy that obsesses them doesn’t exist. but while they wait for it, they’ll try to whip up the winds, and the rest of us will struggle to find shelter. qanon is scary because it’s getting bigger, it’s scary because we don’t know how to stop it, and it’s scary because the people behind it won’t be stopped, and, until their illusory storm arrives, they won’t be satisfied.

molly roberts
the washington post

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
this is to all the survivors of rape. i will not comply to the use of euphemisms. rape starts from that look on that man's face on that street that day to the many times your own boyfriend invited himself into your bed. we all deserve to treat our bodies like jewels - freely.
here's my piece of angst :
*why i don't drink at night*
*
his eyes are red of substance and hormones.
i do not fear him.
i despise him.
for making me the object of his unwanted desire.
for making me dirty.
*
i want to scratch myself out of my body.
peel myself like an orange.
wash my soul.
*
but i can't.
so i despise you.
*
[this statement is gender neutral]
#rape #rapeculture #rapejustice #justice #metoo #mybody #myrights #woman #women #trust #sex #violence #sexualviolence #fear #feminist #feminism #disgust #writer #writing

text:
2018 has been a roller coaster ride for the oppressed and the oppressor, for the helpless and the powerful and for the campaigners and the bashers. from marital rape to homosexuality to #metoo we have come a long way. let us have a look at some of the most important events that india witnessed this year. 
#1 the tax is gone, now it’s just the taboo

the sanitary pads were taxed at 12% under the gst which was launched in july 2017. the decision triggered protests, petitions and court cases that questioned why the government taxed pads as a luxury rather than an essential item, such as condoms, which are tax-free. last year, lawmaker sushmita dev launched a petition to demand a reduction or total removal of taxes on pads, citing that about 70% of the women in the country could not afford them. the government finally scrapped the controversial 12% gst on sanitary pads after a year-long opposition by campaigners. the health of your period is a basic human right, no one should pay for that. women shouldn’t be taxed with something they are born with. the government’s decision to exempt a basic hygiene product like the sanitary napkin from gst is a very big win for everyone across the country.

#2018rewind #highlights #women2018 #taxfreesanitarynapkins #gst #taboo #humanrights #womenite #sushmitadev #bleedfree #taxfreewings #notaluxury

text:
happy and sheroic 2019 from lon-art! last year we achieved more than ever and this was thanks to our amazing team, partners, sponsors and specially to you.
in 2019 we will focus in fighting back injustices and violence towards women through the arts, exhibitions, new museums tours and art workshops. 
hope you will join us!

don't let the patriarchy befall you in 2019!

2019 wishes: we want the museums full of women artists, more solo exhibitions by women artists, more women in the textbooks, and in power, more women marching and appreciating feminism and we want men to join us and fight back with us.

we also want to stop grieving women deaths, we want women to feel free and not fear when walking home alone, we want women to enjoy their bodies and sexuality to the full and don't feel ashamed. we want women not to suffer for being a woman. we want feminism for all, not matter what color, social class, sexuality or gender you belong to. 
#happynewyear #royalacademy #womenartists #womeninart #feminism #feminismforall #niunamenos #metoo #yotecreo #womeninart

text:
❤️news ❤️ "personalmente, ritengo che time's up abbia contribuito a coltivare un senso di comunità tra le donne nel mio settore. le persone assumono che gli attori femminili si conoscono e si incontrano, ma spesso siamo piuttosto isolati in un settore che può sembrare una forza atomizzante piuttosto che un legame. ripensando al momento #metoo spartiacque alla fine del 2017, le donne del settore si stavano avvicinando, condividendo esperienze, organizzando insieme in un modo che non avevo mai visto prima. c'è stata una realizzazione sincera del potere dell'unità, che è qualcosa che le donne in altri settori hanno ovviamente conosciuto da tempo!
il potere di trasformazione della solidarietà si applica anche al rapporto tra hollywood e il mondo più ampio alla fine del 2017. sono stato così ispirato dal modo in cui donne di altre industrie, sfondi e contesti lavorativi erano con noi. hollywood è una bolla privilegiata e gli attivisti potrebbero licenziarci, ma invece ci hanno supportato, fornito indicazioni e aperto a campagne di collaborazione. molte donne ci hanno detto che sentire donne di alto profilo a hollywood parlare di questi problemi li ha incoraggiati a parlare anche loro. questo mi ha reso ancora più impegnato ad alzare la voce. sento che abbiamo il mandato di parlare. se noi, con tutti i nostri privilegi, piattaforme e protezioni non lo chiamiamo, come possiamo aspettarci che gli altri lo facciano?
c'è ancora molta strada da fare, ma mi sento più ottimista ora che abbiamo nuovi strumenti e meccanismi nel nostro settore per proteggere e salvaguardare le persone da molestie e abusi. l'anno scorso è stata introdotta un'intera gamma di linee guida, standard e linee guida - come le linee guida sul bullismo e le molestie bfi adottate dall'industria britannica, il che significa che un giovane attore o assistente luci sul set avrà probabilmente più senso di i loro diritti, i percorsi di ricorso, i mezzi di sostegno ecc. di prima. "

il potere di trasformazione della solidarietà si applica anche al rapporto tra hollywood e il mondo più ampio alla fine del 2017. sono stato così ispirato dal modo in cui donne di altre industrie, sfondi e contesti lavorativi erano con noi. hollywood è una bolla privilegiata e gli attivisti potrebbero licenziarci, ma invece ci hanno supportato, fornito indicazioni e aperto a campagne di collaborazione. molte donne ci hanno detto che sentire donne di alto profilo a hollywood parlare di questi problemi li ha incoraggiati a parlare anche loro. questo mi ha reso ancora più impegnato ad alzare la voce. sento che abbiamo il mandato di parlare. se noi, con tutti i nostri privilegi, piattaforme e protezioni non lo chiamiamo, come possiamo aspettarci che gli altri lo facciano?
c'è ancora molta strada da fare, ma mi sento più ottimista ora che abbiamo nuovi strumenti e meccanismi nel nostro settore per proteggere e salvaguardare le persone da molestie e abusi. l'anno scorso è stata introdotta un'intera gamma di linee guida, standard e linee guida - come le linee guida sul bullismo e le molestie bfi adottate dall'industria britannica, il che significa che un giovane attore o assistente luci sul set avrà probabilmente più senso di i loro diritti, i percorsi di ricorso, i mezzi di sostegno ecc. di prima. "

crediti: emma watson update ❤️ instagram : https://www.instagram.com/we.love.emma.watson.crush/

passate dal nostro gruppo ; https://www.facebook.com/groups/445446642475974/

twitter : https://twitter.com/giacomags/status/90764632

today i had two choices 1. to stay at home and throw my own pity party because i was alone on my birthday, or 2. go and do something i enjoy, and of course no. 2 was the go. i left home at 4.30 this morning and travelled up north, going to 12 beautiful waterfalls that i haven't been to yet. my absolute favourite was the karekare falls just south of piha absolute stunner, and i can't wait to take tara there. i also set myself a challenge as i managed to get to 20 waterfalls in 2018 since i got my little car, and because today i turned 27 my aim was to go to at least 7 different waterfalls, and i well and truly smashed that, so the count is now sitting at 32 waterfalls in the north island. in the past i would have sat at home and sulked, but because i've been making all these awesome positive changes in many aspects of my life, i am about creating my own happiness, it is not up to others to make me happy, i need to make my own happiness.
#nzsummer #zmsummer

text:
this may be a provoking post, but women really get bombarded on a daily basis with men on social media messaging them. i still do, i get many a week, sometimes many a day, both on my personal profile and via this page. generally it begins with an innocent 'hello' or 'how are you madame'... the energy reeks of predatory behaviour and you just know they are doing this to a lot of women online. it makes me cringe if i am honest.⠀
⠀
i have no idea where a certain group of men in the world believe that women want, need or invite this in.⠀
⠀
i used to know a woman who was naive when it came to this, she met him online and then she met the man overseas and he claimed he loved her, she had not become wise to this kind of thing, that he was using her for a passport into the country (not always the reason for contact of this kind).⠀
⠀
yes some men may be lonely, granted, but many women are too but don't message men online because we know it's just not the thing to do.⠀
⠀
when did it become okay?⠀
⠀
follow me on my blog, facebook or twitter or listen to my podcast on itunes (see bio for more info)⠀
⠀

text:
this might be trigering or disturbing for some individuals. read with caution. 
when writing this i embodied my experiences. i acknowledge the differences varied between sex, gender, race, access to health care and location etc. and i apologise. 
sexual assualt is a crime. sexual assault is defined as "sexual assault occurs when a person is forced, coerced or tricked into sexual acts against their will or without their consent,... sexual assault is a crime. sexual assault is not the victim's fault." as defined by the nsw government department of victims services. 
what if i have recently been sexually assaulted or a loved one has opened up about their assault?
the first thing to do is calm down and ask how long ago was the assault. getting yourself to a hospital asap.
((when i speak about the rest of the process i am speaking in a sense of australia /universal public health care. (if someone in the northern america dm about the process there i can pass it along to anyone who might need that resource).) step 1. go to the hospital. don't shower/change/or wash hands. bring a phone charger and headphones! 
step 2. present yourself to triage in the emergency room. the nurse will take your vitals and ask why you're in hospital. the hospitalis a safe place filled with professionals. nurses in emergency room are trained and qualified. i know you can be brave and tell the nurse that you have been sexually assaulted. the nurse will page the on call social worker and continue to ask you questions. such as: what happened in the situation, do you know the attacker/perpetrator, they will also ask if you think you've been drugged or suffered additional wounds e.g. cuts, scrapes, bruises, fractures and tearing. 
step 3: waiting. the on call social worker will be there as support and will link you to services. the social worker will ask you again to describe the situation so they can write a record for their services. 
continues in comments

text:
my mãe and pai soon after they got engaged.

today i honour and give thanks to my mãe and pai, as without them, i wouldn’t be here today. i thank my parents for my portuguese/indian heritage it has brought me closer to understanding myself.

my parents divorced when i was five, it was a bitter divorce. my mãe is my legacy, a beautiful soul and i will be indebted to her for the rest of my life. my pai loved his drink, gambling and women. he was brutal to my mum in front of me. his behaviour ripped our family apart. 
i am here in fatima on a solitude and reflection journey to heal the many broken pieces in my heart. i am here also to forgive the people who changed the course of my life as a child and wounded my soul and heart, my pai and my abuser. today i release both these men from all the pain and suffering they caused me as a child. 
i am letting go of all resentments and anger i have held. i am now free to embrace the new me, a totally freespirit risen from the ashes.

#metoo #mae #pai #mother #father #parents #mum #dad #brokenheart #healing #forgiveness #solitude #reflection #freespirit #me #love #kindness #family #divorce #brokenfamilies #portuguese #indian

text:
#happykwanzaa #happynewyear
i chose my oldest daughters name based on the 7th principle of #kwanzaa "imani" is the substance of things hoped for without the evidence of being seen. #faith #imani 
as a teen mom,  without a living mother, i knew that i had to keep faith with me at all times.

in 5 weeks she will be 18 years old. she will be breaking multiple generational challenges. heading to graduation from high school with acceptance letters from the schools of her choice and honors! 
i'm so proud of her. i'm so blessed to have her in my life. she will be the 1st in her family (on her dads side to go to college & graduate). shes graduating high school without being a teen mom out of 4 generations (or more). i'm thankful for imani in my life. it hasnt been easy the past 18 years but she gives me hope for the future! 
#iamevidence #supremetransitions #endthebacklog #joyfulheart #blessed #detroitlove #everydayimok #metoo #issabeautifullife #healingispossible #freedom #selfcare #seasonschange #letsgohigher

text:
new class alert!! consent seems to be on everyone’s tongue with the #metoo movement and the continuous discourse in the public sphere. it is most often a conversation about sexual harassment and violence or within the context of romantic relationships and sexual encounters. leaving the discussion in the realm of sexual experiences (whether negative or positive) leaves out the importance of consent in our own bodies, families, and workplaces… and the systems that created and reinforce perpetual consent violations. 
join touk keo (founder of the @radmeditationforbipoc and healer) and jess devries (sex and intimacy coach) to take a closer look at general consent including: - what is rape culture? - what conditions reinforce rape culture in individuals and american society as a whole? - when/how did we lose our personal agency? - how can we feel consent in our bodies? - how does being in trauma response affect our ability to give informed consent? - how does consent look different for the bipoc community and for the white community? 
this workshop will provide a framework for the cultural systems that we live in and how to connect with the knowledge of our bodies to help strengthen our personal agency. 
general information: 
date: saturday, january 26th
time: 2:00pm - 4:30pm
location: speec space - 5010 n commercial ave. portland, or 97211
accessibility: the speec space has two steps to enter and the bathroom is not currently ada accessible. it is close to trimet lines 44 and 72.
cost: $10-$30 sliding scale

space is limited. to reserve your spot please use the following link: paypal.me/jessdevries1

tweet_full:
new class alert!! consent seems to be on everyone’s tongue with the #metoo movement and the continuous discourse in the public sphere. it is most often a conversation about sexual harassment and violence or within the context of romantic relationships and sexual encounters. leaving the discussion in the realm of sexual experiences (whether negative or positive) leaves out the importance of consent in our own bodies, families, and workplaces… and the systems that created and reinforce perpetual consent violations. 
join touk keo (founder of the @radmeditationforbipoc and healer) and jess devries (sex and intimacy coach) to take a closer look at general consent including: - what is rape culture? - what conditions reinforce rape culture in individuals and american society as a whole? - when/how did we lose our personal agency? - how can we feel consent in our bodies? - how does being in trauma response affect our ability to give informed consent? - how does consent look different for the bipoc community and for the white community? 
this workshop will provide a framework for the cultural systems that we live in and how to connect with the knowledge of our bodies to help strengthen our personal agency.

text:
#happykwanzaa #happynewyear
i chose my oldest daughters name based on the 7th principle of #kwanzaa "imani" is the substance of things hoped for without the evidence of being seen. #faith #imani 
as a teen mom,  without a living mother, i knew that i had to keep faith with me at all times.

in 5 weeks she will be 18 years old. she will be breaking multiple generational challenges. heading to graduation from high school with acceptance letters from the schools of her choice and honors! 
i'm so proud of her. i'm so blessed to have her in my life. she will be the 1st in her family (on her dads side to go to college & graduate). shes graduating high school without being a teen mom out of 4 generations (or more). i'm thankful for imani in my life. it hasnt been easy the past 18 years but she gives me hope for the future!

text:
i think it's important to revel in all of the amazing things i did in 2018, and also celebrate and learn from the failures. so here is a not comprehensive list of things i did in 2018:
- traveled solo internationally for the first time and was reminded of how much i find wonder in the world and how much i adore traveling alone. not surprisingly, many of my top 9 are from france.
- bought a brand new (!) car.
- continued to treat my body like a trash can. whoops.
- increased my credit score by 50 points, something i truly thought was impossible because of a path i was set on at 17.
- attended some truly phenomenal shows/readings/presentations, with highlights including hannah gadsby, the mcelboys, hank green, samantha irby with lindy west, and sally field.
- really struggled with all of the #metoo stuff, and especially christine blaisey ford's brave testimony.
- did a fairly good job taking care of myself with mental health days when needed as a result.
- got a new vibrator.
- read 130 books.
- failed to be there for friends (at least it felt that way) or flaked a few times.
- celebrated my 3-year anniversary at the 5th, the longest i've stayed in a professional job since i started working 10 years ago.
- cried a lot about the state of the world and especially the lack of empathy i see on a daily basis in our country.
- got a new prescription and new glasses for the first time in 8 years.
- still didn't date anyone because of my joy of being alone and dating is terrible and also childhood issues (see also "trash can body") but did have approximately 10 million crushes on all kinds of people.
- spent way too much time on social media.
- still lacked any semblance of patience.
- visited my bestie in new york where we did absolutely nothing and it was perfect.
- made some really good new friends.
- contemplated the meaning of life and humanity.
- nurtured a neighbourhood cat, bringing her from super skinny to a healthy weight. and fed some raccoons and possums in the process.
- said goodbye to my last grandparent.
- got my first christmas tree as a "grown up."
- had at least one existential crisis a week.
- turned 30! (finally.)

text:
i opted to make my own top nine 🤷🏻‍♀️.
it feels pretty reaffirming to have concrete evidence of how far i’ve come this year. that first post of 2018 was dark. today it requires serious effort to remember the level of pain i was in at the time. funny, it doesn’t require as much effort to bring back the visceral feeling of pure self-love from that second picture. but that is probably because nowadays, i get to tap into that feeling on some level every day💗.
it has been work, and i am taking this moment to be flipping proud of myself!!! 💪🏼.
may 2019 be a year of brighter pictures, brighter smiles, more meditation, and more trees ✨🌳💚.
.
.
.

text:
happy new year!

in much gratitude:
thank you to all of you that have been kind and apart of this journey. 🙇🏻‍♀️🙏 goodbye to 2018 and all the years prior, for all the happy times and  all the pains like an axe that chopped my heart. 'i will never look at you the same way again. i'll never be that girl again.  many things happened, i can't understand why they did or why others have made conscious decisions for their actions and behaviors. such is the strangeness of the human heart.  but every moment was a precious thing, having in it the essence of finality - daphne du maurier

1.  when life is audited, performance improves

2.  define new goals and purpose

3.  change course, starting today

the gift of 2019 for everything you do:
give yourself a new and significant challenge. because your pursuits should be meaningful to you. so direct all that energy to finishing the only work that matters to you.  be kind to yourself. #forbes

thomas monson says, “choose your love, then love your choice.” find the person that magnetically pulls you in. do everything you can to serve and create a deeply beautiful relationship and vision with that person. then never stop investing in that person’s joy and never stop creating a bigger and more powerful vision.

au revoir!

thank you to all of you that have been kind and apart of this journey. 🙇🏻‍♀️🙏 goodbye to 2018 and all the years prior, for all the happy times and  all the pains like an axe that chopped my heart. 'i will never look at you the same way again. i'll never be that girl again.  many things happened, i can not understand why they did or why others have made conscious decisions for their actions and behaviors. such is the strangeness of the human heart.  but every moment was a precious thing, having in it the essence of finality - daphne du maurier

1.  when life is audited, performance improves

2.  define new goals and purpose

3.  change course, starting today

the gift of 2019 for everything you do:
give yourself a new and significan not challenge. because your pursuits should be meaningful to you. so direct all that energy to finishing the only work that matters to you.  be kind to yourself. #forbes

thomas monson says, “choose your love, then love your choice.” find the person that magnetically pulls you in. do everything you can to serve and create a deeply beautiful relationship and vision with that person. then never stop investing in that person’s joy and never stop creating a bigger and more powerful vision.

au revoir!

text:
today we talk about being a woman in any field ; be it medical, law, teaching , any profession , or even at home . #asawoman 
#asawoman , i love this picture because it is a selfie my three year old son took of his nanny, my housekeeper , him and me. this, right here is seemless parenting, that @indranooyiofficial talks about. i have taught my housekeeper every little nuance, from how to read children’s books, revise his school poems and even cook for the house hold, such that it is seemless . today she has made prawn biryani for lunch and the spices are a bit much. i explained to her that for a chicken biryani the onions can be browned, the spices more vibrant, but for a delicate seafood like prawns the spices are milder. these simple and small tips, will make her cooking and mine almost seemless and identical. that would mean my family would not miss ‘ma ke haath ka khaana’. many women will hold back what they know , but by giving my all, i support her . 
on the last day of work, a fellow colleague in the operation theatre wished me happy new year, and then added “ i wish you have another child this year.” #asawoman i would wish another female colleague , more success at work, that her paper get published, her presentation goes well, that she manage to get that great new machine for her practice, that she go on fabulous holidays and also pay off her emi. 
#asawoman i have been taught to ignore these male chauvinists, but i wish inhad replied with a “ same to you.” and see ya expression when a male doctor is wished he have another child this year, rather than professional success. 
#asawoman i don’t expect less from myself, but i definitely expect more from others ; to step up. 
i read in the papers today that over 3,50,000 women in kerala formed a unique #womenswall across 620 km to support equality of gender , and a parallel ‘solidarity wall’ was formed by men in some parts of the state as well. let’s form that wall #asawoman , even if it’s on social media. 
this year , i hope to share how i manage my work, home, and everything in between #asawoman and support other women as they strike that balance. 
thankyou @nataliecrawfordmd , joining in from india .
name: Dr Kuheli Bhattacharya

text:
it’s been on my mind a lot lately, about wishing i could say these words to a certain someone. 
to the complete stranger who showed me that there is still humanity in this world. i wish i could thank you. - today marks 2 years since my life drastically changed. for the better. that stranger was a part of that day. 
this person’s voice is vivid in my mind. almost every time i’m in my car alone and stop at a light i can still hear it so clearly. 
at the time i was assaulted, i was in the passenger seat of our car. we were stopped at a light when my ex was hitting me. i could hear someone from the car next to us yelling “what are you doing, what are you doing to her”. next thing i remember is our car swerving around. when i asked my ex why he was driving so fast he responded with “i’m  trying to get away from the person tailing us”. although to this day i do not know if he attempted to notify police or how long he chased after our car or what he thought he would be able to do to help me.

but, the point is, there is someone out there who i wish i could make aware how thankful i am. thankful they saw something and wanted to try and actually do something for another human being they didn’t even know. 
#thankyou #thrivingnotjustsurviving #domesticviolenceawareness

thank you @ktcavalli for helping me with this photo & continued help toward the gallery ❤️.

text:
dylan aka silly dilly mcwilly aka dyl-dyl crossed over the rainbow bridge on december 31st at 10:30am. 
a joker and a gentleman, he was a frisbee master, a gooser-greeter, a natural-born healer, a sock eater and chicken carcass stealer. he herded his kibble, compulsively made friends and helped me host years of parties. faster than the greyhounds at the dog park, dylan raced the wind and sometimes...he won. 
dylan reminded me to look for the happy. taught me how to live life in the present. made me smile with his snarfle-snort greetings. and helped me heal from my own #metoo with his unconditional love. he laid his head where he found hurting hearts and showed me how to really see the people around me. 
he spent his last christmas surrounded by family ... and stopped eating the next day. a trip to the vet confirmed what our hearts already knew. he was dying. two aggressive cancer clusters in his organs. 
we took him to the beach for his last two outings. he laid on a towel and enjoyed the smells until he decided to go for one last swim in the bay. and lickety split, the dog who hadn’t walked for 3 days, took himself right down to the water and plonked in. i helped him paddle around until he decided it was enough. 
the vet came the next morning. snuggled up with us on the couch, he greeted the vet with a tired wag and sigh. listening to “over the rainbow” by iz, we hugged and kissed him as he looked at us for the last time and exhaled. 
16 years of love. 
my best friend. 
a most beautiful soul. 
i’ll always love you my precious boy. the world feels emptier without you.

ps...i hope the angels know how to throw frisbees! 
#ilovehimsomuch #adoptdontshop #bestwoof #myheart

text:
tellervo koivisto täyttää tänään 90 vuotta!💐
▪️
syntymäpäivähaastattelussa tellervo koivisto puhuu muun muassa vaikeista kouluajoistaan. opiskelun iloa varjosti vuosien ajan uskonnon opettajan, pastori lauri jokisen, väkivaltainen kurinpito ja ahdistelu.
▪️
jari tervon haastattelussa koivisto kertoo inhottavista käynneistä pappilan kansliassa, joihin kuului syyllistämistä ja väkivaltaa. "sitten hän istui korkeaan tuoliin ja veti minut siihen polvilleen. pylly paljaaksi, käden ojennus, ruoska sieltä ja alkoi piestä."
▪️
erityisen ahdistava oli tilanne, jossa pastori kyseli 13-vuotiaan tytön kuukautisista. "se oli siihen aikaan, se oli jotain niin kamalaa, että minä ilmeisesti rupesin suureen ääneen vaan huutamaan, että ei, ei, ei, ja pääsin sieltä ulos", koivisto muistelee edelleen järkyttyneenä.
▪️
tellervo koivisto uskaltautui puhumaan painajaismaisista kokemuksista ensimmäistä kertaa viime vuonna. siihen rohkaisi kansainvälinen #metoo-kampanja.
▪️
lue lisää ja katso haastattelu osoitteessa yle.fi – linkki biossa! jari tervon haastattelussa tellervo kertoo myös romanttisesta ensikohtaamisestaan edesmenneen miehensä mauno koiviston kanssa. #yleuutiset : intervisio

text:
a few years ago i made the biggest change ever in my life by deciding to break free from a toxic relationship that was killing me physically, mentally, emotionally, and spiritually. since then,  i've had to adjust and survive as a single mother of three along with juggling day to day obstacles. but, i learned how to make it work and have been living a happier and healthier life since. now, i'm no stranger to overcoming challenges and leaving a toxic relationship was just one of the many struggles i've had to overcome. 
join on january 16 @ 7pm est for my free webinar where we will discuss the tools and resources i used to walk away from a toxic relationship, become a published author, and begin the journey to creating the life i always wanted. the first five people to sign up will receive a free copy of my book let mia tell it and everyone will receive my 30 day breaking toxic cycles journal for free! 
i can't wait to grow and elevate with you and assist you with breaking the cycles that has been holding you back and keeping you from living your best life! *select the linktree in my bio to sign up!!!! author/motivational speaker/blogger
mira cassidy

what is rape culture? rape culture is a set of cultural norms that are present in cultures that don't discourage rape. (they dont encourage rape, but sexual predators are not punished enough). there are a few things that are present in many rape cultures. 1. victim blaming. saying the victim is responsible. 2. saying "boys will be boys". this is one of the biggest problems. this ideology says that all boys do this, so why punish it? this is one of the reasons that rapists get such light punishment. 3. continuing to support rapists. this is very clear in hollywood, where people like louis c.k. are still given standing ovations despite being a predator. this also contributes to why some rapists have such light punishment. 4. catcalling and other forms of verbal harassment are said to be "just friendly" this isn't true.

text:
"2019 brings no changes for natural beauty"
wow! a new year for a new you, right? well not for me 👀 as i decided years ago that once i gained my healing after brokenness i would no longer wear masks to hide who i am or be who the world wants me be 🙌 i stopped perming my natural my hair about 12 years ago & honey i don't have the time or the energy to get up every morning to put on make up 😜 i may sew some hair in to be extra every now & then or paint my lips to be doing something but over all i love my gray semi nappy-wavy hair, all my freckles, wrinkles & every thing that you may look at as my imperfections...i look at them as my uniqueness.  this is what makes me special & even in this new year there will be no changes for the natural beauty that god has created me to be.  so don't compare me to beyonce let beyonce be to me 🤙🙌 i'm not a hater but an appreciator of who god created me to be. so here i am walking in 2019 with my hair not combed, face not made up, no botox or permanent make up because there will be no changes for natural beauty💖💖💖 learn to appreciate who you are & how created you...unique & wonderfully made 🙌  happy new year🎉🎉🎉 #lifecoach #livelovelaugh #metoo #mentalhealth #youarebeautiful #setyoutstandards #changesarenotneccessary #survivor #blacklove #blackgirlmagic #blackgirlsrock #loveyou #noperms #creamycrack #daretobeyou #ilovejesus #iloveme #laviniaspeaks

text:
our society has come a long way in reducing the stigma around mental illness, but we still have a long way to go. many misconceptions and stereotypes relating to mental illness still exist.

so why does it matter? stigma can impact people’s desire to seek treatment. stigma can cause those with mental health disorders to isolate themselves or develop negative thoughts and perceptions. it can also impact access to evidence-based treatment options.

we all can make an impact in our communities and society to reduce stigma. read on to learn more about how to reduce self-stigma and public stigma around mental health disorders. https://youwillbearwitness.com/2019/01/02/overcoming-stigma-associated-with-mental-illness/ #youwillbearwitness #metoo #ptsd #peterfox #ptsdsurvivor #ptsdrecovery #ptsdawareness #stopracism #stopbullying #stopchildabuse #doitfordolly #trauma #therapydog #emdr #erinfado

text:
hello warrior women & all who support us!

i have started warrior women because i want all women to have a voice and to know a community of women exists to support, accept and love one another. below is a bit of my story and what has driven me to create warrior women on a mission.

when i was 13 years old i was sexually assaulted by a family member. six counts of sexual assault. i lost a lot by turning in my assailant. half of my family stood behind the adult assailant who had a prior history of similar actions. nearly every adult around me told me put what happened behind me and move forward, which was impossible. i was lost and i trusted the wrong people. one even told me i should kill myself because i was worthless. going through all of this was made even more difficult by the people in my household. my mother has always been self involved (and addicted to something my whole life) and my step-father never liked me (he literally would get angry if i accidentally walked down the hallway at the same time he did). both were physically and emotionally abusive at different times of my like. i often felt i did not belong anywhere.

by the grace of god, strong adult influences, a few family members and friends (who are my  family) i survived and made it to adulthood. however, just because i turned 18 and could move out (which i did the day i turned 18) i was not ok, not even close (to see more of the story, please go to the warrior women on a mission facebook page). while going through all of this i realized the most crippling feeling is shame. i really evaluated why i felt shame and a few things came up…the silence. i often stay silent because i am afraid of what people will think when they find out. the lack of education leads to a variety of reactions…some are silent and some have said “oh”. the worst reaction was when someone said i did not need to know that, i cannot help you. well, i have decided i want to educate everyone possible! i want to build a community of support for any woman who need to be reminded of the warrior she is! thank you for reading my story and for supporting warrior women on a mission! #warriorwomenmission #wwmaz #metoo

text:
so many
different dreary worlds,
that it’s hard to make a choice,
hard to choose at all,
hard to have to.

ahh, that’s it isn’t it? choice.
the great commanding curse
of freedom. it’s very source.

no freedom without it,
only a painful apathy,
with no worry, and no hope.

for hope is always tight with worry,
hope and dread, did i make the right choice?
did i choose wrongly? the stress, anxiety
over the future, over it’s hope.

yet, and still, there are no wrong choices,
just fleeting, frozen moments.
forever, and without changes,
with no way to make them.

so don’t worry,
just choose and go, follow
freedom’s path to the next choice,
and don’t worry,
enjoy the hope.

sandra osborne

text:
as we step foot into the new year i can’t wait to see what 2019 has in store for me as a new mother, lover and daughter of god and my family.💕 in early 2018 i closed a dreadful chapter of my life. many people don’t know that i am a survivor of sexual assault. two years ago i wouldn’t have even thought about saying it out loud in an empty room. and for the past two years i faced many struggles that challenged my education, my physical and mental health, friendships and personal relationships. it wasn’t easy, especially in the mist of #metoo headlines that faded into thin air the moment the next trending topic came along. ever week showcased a new survivor and every week we forgot about the last. i felt like a stranger in my own skin and felt zero relatedness to any of them.

soon as my case came to a close, i said #enough to many of my toxic traits, people and habits. i learned to trust my soul and listen to the rhythm of my heart beat. i took to god many of my worries and pain. in return i was blessed with two of the most beautiful miracles. 
ryan and our baby. 
the most beautiful blessings to set foot in my life and heart. it’s been a year full of awakening moments. some challenging. but most of them joyful! through all the hardships, ryan stood by my side and together we’ve worked a foundation based on love, respect and mutual support. forever my love bug. 😘

2018 taught me to speak up for myself🗣. live in the moment🧘🏽‍♀️. love unconditionally❤️. take risks. challenge my career through different avenues. budget my lifestyle and make better financial decisions. i learned to trust in god’s word and make a life surrounded by like minded people✨. in 2018 i laughed. i cried. i felt pain, i felt helpless. i felt vulnerable. i felt joy. i felt love. i felt fear at the sight of almost miscarrying. i experienced the first movements of my baby swimming in my womb. felt my baby’s first kicks👣. i walked the stage accompanied by my two sisters 👯. i received my bachelors degree👩🏻‍🎓. i bought my first car. landed my first full-time job as a college graduate. put up our first christmas tree in our new place and spent the new year cuddled in bed sound asleep. 🌙
name: Bello 🌙

text:
"𝘓𝘦𝘢𝘳𝘯 𝘵𝘩𝘪𝘴 𝘧𝘳𝘰𝘮 𝘸𝘢𝘵𝘦𝘳: 𝘭𝘰𝘶𝘥 𝘴𝘱𝘭𝘢𝘴𝘩𝘦𝘴 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘣𝘳𝘰𝘰𝘬 𝘣𝘶𝘵 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘰𝘤𝘦𝘢𝘯𝘴 𝘥𝘦𝘱𝘵𝘩 𝘢𝘳𝘦 𝘤𝘢𝘭𝘮"
-buddha

happy new year! something that's always been apart of my life is bodies of water. oceans, lakes, ponds, rivers, creeks. water has the capacity to destroy and provide. i almost drowned when i was 5. yet, i spent nearly every summer from 7-18 swimming in a river. i can heal from that accident and go onto love something i was afraid of. i had to make changes and face my anxiety about the water hurting me again. it's no different than other parts of my life. accidents happen and i will get hurt (most often times emotionally). that's a part of life, and it's hard to accept when things change. it's been even harder to do so because a lot of the changes in my life weren't from decisions i made. one of my resolutions is to stop white-knuckling life. if i spend so much time anxious about the past repeating itself, then i'm going to miss out on opportunities to make positive change in my life. 𝘐'𝘷𝘦 𝘣𝘦𝘦𝘯 𝘥𝘰𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘵𝘩𝘪𝘴 𝘧𝘰𝘳 𝘺𝘦𝘢𝘳𝘴 𝘯𝘰𝘸, 𝘴𝘰 𝘐'𝘮 𝘯𝘰𝘵 𝘦𝘹𝘱𝘦𝘤𝘵𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘪𝘵 𝘵𝘰 𝘨𝘰 𝘢𝘸𝘢𝘺 𝘴𝘰𝘰𝘯. however, i'm finding small steps to take to feel more safe in the world without relying on avoidance. both my art and what i do with my spare time will reflect this. i'm working towards healing and i will have raging tides as well as still waters. i can have both and still be making progress. 
#tradtionalart #river #water #ocean #tide #selfgrowth #selfcare #newyearsresolutions2019 #mindfulness #mentalhealth #mentalhealthrecovery #ptsd #ptsdrecovery #positivity #healing #womenarestrongashell #metoo #metoomovement #depression #smallsteps #cleareyed

text:
grateful to begin the new year at a yoga practice at #bldg7yoga today. awesome practice! 
it was a busy day. i had some really treasured connected moments which make me excited for the year to come. 
i’m also super pumped for the berks me too:a time to heal movement. please stay tuned this week. i’ll be including the link to the lineup of presenters (come see me speak at the miller center on march 30th! and thank you to all you men out there who haven’t quite learned about boundaries, for the many many random weird inappropriate and sometimes sexually aggressive messages i’ve gotten from those of you i don’t know over the last month. even pics of you naked! today i got a pic of someone’s butt. 🤣just what i always wanted in my ig mailbox! a strange mans butt! you’ve given me so much more good content for my me too talk and for that i am grateful! please remember i’ll have a powerpoint!). happy new year everyone! 2019 likely is still going to have some huge challenges from the looks of it, but i am excited for the new opportunities on the horizon!

text:
my story pt.2
my younger cousins noticed that i had a huge red stain on my pants and started asking me if it was juice or if i cut myself really badly or if i was in pain. i forgot to mention that they always said that if i say no that they will cry and that they felt physical pain and said that if i said anything about it that their mom will punish them(i'm black so an ass whopping is something that everyone feared). i always said no even though i know that the older ones have been touching me and using me for pleasure. when my mother for home the younger ones told her and she drove me to the hospital and brought me to the emergency room. on the way there i wasn't allowed to sit down. i remember the doctor asking me the same questions that my younger cousins and mother asked me. i denied all of them and moved on  with my life. few years prior to the incidents my mom showed me a video about consent, sex and rape. after that everything became clearer to me. the night she showed me the video i told her about my cousins and she took me to therapy from our pastor's wife. it didn't really help because they would openly talk about my situation during church. my mom left the church after it ruined her marriage, embarrassed me  and stole money from her. last year at my old school boys would touch my but and breast and trigger me giving me flash backs and i didn't trust any guys at school. to anyone reading rape  is not the victim's fault. no means no. drunk and unable to reply means no. change of thought means no. this really needs to stop. what the victim is wearing should not matter. it's the men and women who rapes people who should be looked at not the victims. if you are going through anything please tell someone it might make you feel better. dm if you want to rant or talk💖

text:
january is human trafficking awareness month. watch what the veterans think about human trafficking below:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6yifvqrtb7g&list=uujhpyzwepfg2tktiujj7x3w 
according to unicef usa, the 2009 u.s. state department trafficking in persons report cited a london-based study, which found that almost 70% of adult female trafficking victims experienced domestic violence prior to being trafficked. 
the victims of abuse can’t leave if they don’t have a place to go. hope pyx global is that place dedicated to helping victims and survivors of domestic abuse from all backgrounds. 
for more information, visit: 
https://www.hopepyxglobal.org

text:
the transition from 2018 to 2019 was like a slow motion trainwreck for me. 🙈
.
2018 threw some major curveballs my way with scant recovery time in between: my first major surgery, the uncovering of abuse and scandal within a religious group that was a huge part of my formative early adult years, and the sudden death of one of my best friends.
.
even without these life stressors, 2018 would have been challenging enough. it’s only been 3 years since i left my abuser, and my recovery still requires what feels like all of my energy and intention.
.
losing jill so tragically—at the hands of the mental health providers who were supposed to be helping her— has sent me into a spiral of grief and anxiety that couldn’t neatly be laid to rest at the end of 2018. it feels wild and important and scary and devastating. this new trauma has rubbed against the shrapnel already in my system, and my c-ptsd symptoms have reared their ugly head again. i’m stable right now but know i need to pursue extra treatment and support at the onset of 2019 to better manage my triggers. i want to integrate and heal. ✨
.
i know by experience that life goes on, even after loss and trauma and death. integration is possible—the commingling of joy and suffering. acceptance is the gateway. but it’s hard work.
.
i acknowledge that 2018 brought many joys with it along with my these hardships, but i will save those gratitudes for another post. right now, it’s important for me to publicly express my grief as i process jill’s death and how this loss has shaken me to my core. 💔
.
i want this first post of the year to be blatantly honest about my mental health struggles right now, and i hope it encourages all of you who are also struggling this winter. the pressure to be optimistic at the start of a new year isn’t always helpful and can feel isolating if you’re just trying to get through the day. be gentle with yourself and know you aren’t the only one thinking “good riddance, 2018. what a dumpster fire of a year.”

text:
have you seen that video of the first 2019 baby born at the guatemalan hospital? no way am i sharing that *tw - if you haven’t seen it, be mindful about investing your energy there. i caught it unaware and it’s traumatic. my purpose in discussing it here is because i know many will have seen it and are now reeling from their emotional, bodily and soul reaction to it

so let’s talk groupthink and vicarious trauma 
when you get a hungry pack of adrenalin fuelled egos together, people lose touch with their values and themselves. they get swept up in the group pull to achieve an outcome. the brain narrows its focus to a mere pinprick of detail and nothing else matters except the win. in this case, getting the first photo of the first 2019 baby

it’s now emblazoned in my mind as flashbulb memory. yet another piece of cultural narrative showing humans at their worst that i have to explain to my daughters one day. like a picture of a child running down the street, naked, covered in napalm

to me, the look on that mama’s face was one of learned helplessness. defeat. horror. pain, distress and complete dismissal of human rights as a room full of people took full advantage to party and capture the moment 
this is what an absence of informed consent looks like. this is what groupthink looks like. the stanford prison experiment. the milgram experiment. when you know there’s a voice inside just one person screaming “this isn’t right”. but they go along with it. it’s cult behaviour 
how is it any different to the glorification of sexual violence with selfies? 
my tolerance for trauma is freakishly high. it has to be. working with the sights, sounds, smells and out of body experiences of trauma is what i do

yet i am grieving and devastated for this mama and her baby. for all the people who will watch this video and add it to their collective consciousness about who  has the power in the birth space 
#birthtrauma #ptsd #vicarioustrauma #birthworker #secondarytrauma #metoo #endobstetricviolence #birthrights 
@birthmonopoly @birthwithoutfear @the_angela_gallo

text:
happy new year!

2019 has just begun and we already have projects lined up. one, filming next week, is our next micro-short in the life improvised series, capturing the small moments that make up life, love, relationships.

this one is called xchange and deals with a powerful woman and her encounter with an escort. we're excited to finally be working with vanessa de largie in the lead role.

vanessa de largie has been the resident sex columnist at maxim magazine since february 2017. 
she's an award-winning actress and author.  she's also a prolific journalist and social commentator.

vanessa's work primarily focuses on fierce female sexuality and gender politics. 
her feature articles regularly appear in the spectator, the daily telegraph, the huff post and penthouse magazine.

www.vanessadelargie.net

we're also reuniting with @frankfazio
from @in_corpore_film to complete the cast and @gerardmackfilmcomposer
and stephen ramplin from @friendsfoesfireworks on crew. it's a melbourne reunion and we can't wait to film!

#lifeimprovised #nexusproductiongroup #microshorts #relationshipdrama #xchange #improvisedfilm #improvacting #melbourne #writer #sexlife #actor #acting #sexcolumnist #melbourneactor #metoo #timesup #womenwholead

text:
as i reflect over the past year (hell, the past few years) and what 2018 has brought me, i've learned to never discount your support system, ones who will circle the wagons for you. no matter if it be one or twenty-one... it's about the depth of commitment to each other not the numbers in your wagon circle. i often think about the hardships the pioneers must've endured but also the joys of knowing at the end of the day they had each other... i can only imagine the stories that were told around the campfires at night.. ** circle the wagons

wagon trains crossing the plains parked their wagons in a tight circle at night for two reasons. the circle was a somewhat defensible, makeshift fort, in case the company came under attack. and it formed a sort of corral, to keep cattle and other livestock from scattering. **
i'm grateful to those who:
-helped me through panic attacks, coming to my aid when i reluctantly called for help. -gave me a kick in the ass when i was being unreasonable and hard headed
-loved me when i was unlovable.
-sat with me in silence because that was what i needed at that moment.
-inspired me to be a better mom.
-traveled with me and listened to me drone on and on about who knows what.
-gave me distractions -let me be there for you when you needed my support.
-encouraged me to create more art
-gave me cuddles
**
i can't say that 2019 will be my year or the best year yet.. all i can say is i now have hope. i have the hope that i will continue to heal, to grow, to love, to live, to survive and work towards thriving. and when it comes time to circle my wagons may i have the foresight to do so and may we weather the storm or difficulty or attack together with strength, love, understanding and grace.
...
...
...
...
...
...
...
...
...
...
...

text:
i took break from social media while ago because of my depression and becuase of other horrible events in my life. and that break helped me a lot. in that period, i gave time to myself. i processed my thoughts and just healed. i thought i won't be able to stay without instagram and snapchat and other apps because i was so addicted to it but it felt better to just take a break from it and stay with myself. i figured lots of things during the break. i came back as a different person and also i started this account thinking that i might help few people you know. i am proud i did that. so if necessary take a break, it is completely okay.

text:
dear 2018,

thank you. thank you for the man that nearly tore me in two. thank you for the love that pushed me to reach for me so that in the aftermath i stand strong in: i am. thank you for the new home, the old one, and the sisters who held my heart when i couldn’t cry anymore. thank you for the lovers and the haters, thank you for the stories on stage and the stories shared. thank you for two new nieces and one lost grandmother. thank you for the process of shedding identity so i am more authentically me, brilliant and bright, regardless of what they see. thank you for me. thank you security. thank you for lore. thank you for the many women who graced the @empowerhertoday stage - i will never be the same - the listeners will never be the same - our city will never be the same. thank you for #metoo. thank you for the rallies and the sacred circles. thank you for wise women who reminded me that i am wild. thank you for strong men who stood beside me and bared their souls. thank you for poetry and prose. thank you for loss. thank you for hozier and sweden. thank you for detroit and ann arbor and louisville and chicago and pittsburgh and new york city and raleigh and florence and lake cumberland and cincinnati and copenhagen. thank you for baseball and basketball and football and track and ballroom dancing. thank you for @aileron_org and dayton entrepreneurs. thank you for @levittdayton and the i love you mural (@tiffanyallynartist ) and @thebrightsidedayton and dayton culture works and @updayton and dayton history fight night and this city. thank you for riverscape and flying pizza and the steelers in cincinnati and 2.0 and chillicothe and ludlow falls. thank you for #themoth and @truetheatre and @doubleedged and @pkdayton and #storyslamdayton and @daytonpoetryslam and @sparkfairborn and @bigbigstoryconsulting and @nucleusdayton . thank you for the miles on my car. thank you for the dollars in the bank. thank you for my red heels. thank you for my health. thank you for my family. thank you for my friends. thank you for my growth. thank you.

sincerely,
2019

text:
so i originally made this paper stretcher as a backdrop for a figure drawing of ian; ian agreed to pose for me and then never showed up. that was 7 months ago. 
i was very perturbed. i put the paper canvas out of site. 
today was one of the most awful new year’s days i’ve ever had. so i got to thinking—i obsessively listen to “welcome to the black parade” by @my.chemicalromance ; it’s about sacrifice, suffering, and continuing on. 
i am tired of being victimized for painting nudes, and i viewed rembrandt’s self portraits yesterday. so, i thought, in this #metoo era, why not use my body as a canvas and adhere myself? here is the result. the paint body blue & red stripes represent the ones in the @my.chemicalromance black parade video. i hope you like it.  i love you all, instagram people—what would i do without you?! #canvaspainting #mychemicalromance #art#arte#kunst 
#paper#art#arte#wings#oilpastel#create#beauty#bodyart#fly#arttherapy#dessin#drawing#painting#life#lavida#people#disappointment#people
name: espressoeasel

text:
hey family! first project of the year is a one act that i will be directing and it's a doozy!!!! #theassaults is written by marilynn anselmi and stars kirrin tubo and lena enck at the secret theatre in long island city, queens.
synopsis: shel talks tonya into reporting an on-campus sexual assault to the newly formed women's center director. the reveal of the alleged prepetrator forces the director to face her own personal choices. 
opening thursday jan 3rd at 7:30pm, the show also runs saturday, january 5th at 3pm and friday, january 11th at 8pm. tickets are 20.00 and there is a concession stand with wine and snacks. you can purchase your tix online or at the door. link in my bio! 
and our play is under the aea showcase code, so equity folks feel free to come out and support! you will be seated once all paid attendees are in. audience votes will get us into the finals to compete for awards and prizes! hope to see you there!!! #secrettheatre #metoo #indietheatre #ourstoriesmatter #aea #unionactor #idirect #iproduce #iact #actors #blacktressmagic #offoffbroadway #wayoffbroadway lol
name: Okema T. Moore

text:
happy new year 🌬🌧💧💦🕊
.
seagulls and ravens, soaring
wishing everyone moments of soaring
in whatever way you soar
.
#2019 #seagulls #ravens #soar #free #freedom #bekind .
.
i once watched robins at a golf course in houston, texas, on a very windy day, jump up and soar a bit, over and over.
.
.
"they flew away over a great dark forest, which stretched to the shore of the sea." hans christianandersen, "the wild swans" (1838)
.
🌲🌲
.
"withering to my desires
i fix on the silence
when birds of fire
spring from my tree."
- jean genet, "funeral march" (1942)
.
book end quotes #penttisammallahti
.

text:
intimacy.

this is my word, prayer, intention, for 2019.

last year was “remember”. and looking back i can see the power of this prayer by its unique, yet deep simplicity.

so, i want to share with you something very personal and intimate that happened and that only my close friends know about.

as i set this intention in january 2018, i was going to embark on a long sexual trauma practitioner training and tantric exploration.

the remembering came in june 2018, when during a training and practice session i discovered (i remembered) that i was sexually abused by a few men when i was a child #metoo.

the trauma memory was in the depth of my body, hidden from my conscious mind. needless to say, that the experience was very intense and yet i discovered, in the horror of the trauma, the blessing it brought for my path and my calling.

it allowed me to finally understand so many of my behaviors, from my fear (and anger) towards powerful & strong men, to my capacity to feel an infinite depth of empathy for sexually abused people.

i also felt immense gratitude for the close friends who showed up during that time to hold me and realized how essential it was/is in my healing process (as it is for all trauma victims). i felt also that the past 15 years of deep spiritual work, allowed me to be able to hold my trauma in a container of light, of love, and of deep tenderness.
.
so this year my word is intimacy.
.
intimacy with...
.
(end of post in my blog, link in instagram bio profile)
. ❤️

text:
fall in love with your life this year guys

in 2018...
1- for the first time in 10,000 years, the majority of humankind is no longer poor or vulnerable to falling into poverty.
2- global suicide rates have dropped by 38% since 1994, saving four million lives.
3- six in 10 of the world’s countries are now democratic—a post war record.
4- the impunity of powerful men to harass and assault women continued to be challenged by the #metoo movement.
5- when the executive branch attempted to allow the separation of children and parents at the border and blockage of asylum requests, democratic and republican judges said no.

text:
these are not my #topnine instead i put together moments that meant a lot to me this past year but also things that reminded me of what i’d like to accomplish in 2019. •i got my motorcycle endorsement and first bike, tattoo’d a little reminder to myself, on myself, celebrated 3 of my beautiful friends marriages to their loves, was diagnosed with ptsd, finally told my story of sexual & physical abuse, the dems took over the house and finally one last hang with some of my ladies. •these reminded me that life is short. i need to enjoy it to the fullest. •this year i will ride more, remember to breathe and really focus on myself and healing, keep fighting and standing up for those who battle mental illness and who suffer from ptsd, stop hiding my views/beliefs because i’m afraid of what others will say, spend time with my friends and family more and finally, attempt to find love again.

text:
my tiny drawing of the essence of woman.
this woman is appreciated and trusted for her love, gentleness, nurturing and compassion.
she carries age-old wisdom and intuition with her as part of her being to help to balance our out-of-kilter world.
she takes no power away from men but seeks to add hers to theirs - to be complimentary. there's no reason to worry or fear.

she's never been abused: emotionally or physically. never has she been vilified in society for demanding equality; never ridiculed because of her bodily functions; never had her life-choices dictated by powerful old white men; never disparaged for demanding justice; never denied freedom of choice because of her gender.
never demonized.

never sexually abused as a child, never silenced by her partner by beating; never raped; never had to try to heal her child after a sexual predator has attacked; never disrespected just because she is female.

text:
january 1, 2019
it’s a perfectly magical, quiet and snowy day for introspection. 
i honestly didn’t know if i was going to make it to today. 
there were so many days last year, mostly in the first half, where i just fought to make it to the end of the day without daydreaming of all the ways that i could put a permanent end to my pain. 
i didn’t know if i would make it to a day where all of my thoughts were not directed towards pushing though the fire and fog of pain and weakness; and trying not to injure myself further- intentionally or not. 
i discovered a new love for sunsets.
they were a bright and brilliant reminder that i had made it to the end of another day; that there was still beauty and magic and wonder despite feeling like life was shrouded in unchangeable darkness. 
i was living in the worst of the what ifs:
what if my life is always life this?
what if i become worse and end up permanently disabled? how will i work and provide for myself? 
what if no one else can handle this and i have to deal with this alone for the rest of my life?

and worse
what if i become a person i don’t recognize- will i let pain and inability make me bitter, angry, and joyless? 
what if i become a burden on everyone i know and no one can stand me?
what if i let this defeat me and end it for good?  how much pain would my family be in?  how could i hurt them like that?

every day i had to choose to fight for a life and future hope that i could not yet see. 
as i am looking back on this year, i see the hardships and what all i lost, i would never want to repeat it, but as i am coming out on the other side- still struggling forward, but now with hope; i see that i have learned to fight for myself like never before. 
i have learned the ability to look for and hold onto the good- in every situation.
i have learned that i don’t always have to be the strong one.
i have learned to let people into my true reality- weakness, ugliness and all; but understand that i am the only one who can carry it all the time. other people have their own shit to deal with and my pain does not stop the world from turning. ha!
i have learned a patient strength...

text:
via @audreaming2 "my tiny drawing of the essence of woman.
this woman is appreciated and trusted for her love, gentleness, nurturing and compassion.
she carries age-old wisdom and intuition with her as part of her being to help to balance our out-of-kilter world.
she takes no power away from men but seeks to add hers to theirs - to be complimentary. there's no reason to worry or fear.

she's never been abused - emotionally or physically. never has she been vilified in society for demanding equality; never ridiculed because of her bodily functions; never had her life-choices dictated by powerful old white men; never disparaged for demanding justice; never denied freedom of choice because of her gender.
never demonized.

never sexually abused as a child, never silenced by her partner by beating; never raped; never had to try to heal her child after a sexual predator has attacked; never disrespected just because she is female. "

text:
this new years eve rather than partying and making resolutions i don’t intend to keep, i reflected. a lot. with that reflection came a lot of tears. my entire life i made decisions based on how it would benefit other people. it’s all i have known. 
you see, i was born a light into a world of chaos. so from very early on i used my gift of bringing love and light to so many others even when it meant sacrificing my own needs. over the years though i became tired. really fucking tired. which is why i decided to change.

i have experienced some of the darkest pains. i have endured trauma, alone. more times than i could count. and while it made me hard in the sense that i didn’t let people all the way in. i never stopped sharing the love i have inside of me. because i truly want you to be happy. i want you to feel loved. 
death. divorce. verbal abuse. rape. molestation. emotional and physical abuse. multiple suicide attempts. abandonment. betrayal. and so much more. yet i still love. i love so fucking hard and i always will. do you know why? because that is what i choose. i choose love. you can too. 
happy new year. sending you so much love and light. 💛 #chooselove #love #light #happynewyear #2019 #metoo #iamchristinefrancis

text: we are researching for a new blog in 2019. this passage from the second sex (de beauvoir, 1949) is the passage that debunks freud’s theories of female penis envy. a theory postulated in the 1800s, debunked in the 1940s is experiencing a resurgence in the 2010s because of some psychologist (jordan peterson) who is trying to make psychology great again (it won’t be great again until the dsm is broken down and re-written, and if you don’t know what that is, don’t talk to me about jordan peterson). according to de beauvoir and her contemporaries, women are not traumatised by or envious of the phallus, unless you give them cause. to a “woman” (cis or trans) this seems so simple, almost logical even, because it explains a woman’s anger. post #metoo there is a new push to whip men into shape, to redefine masculinity. however it is no longer helpful to define masculinity in an specific way... because it simply doesn’t exist. you can be strong when you need to be, you can be vulnerable when you need to be... these traits are not gendered, they are present in all humans, the moment you attribute gender to them, is where the toxicity begins. disabusing young men and women of their gendered upbringing is a hard task, but we all go through it in the end as we grow up and self-actualise. those who cling to societal constructs are those that are disillusioned in the end. this man is trying to make men less “toxic” by re-assigning gender to men who are confused and angry about feminism and their place in the world. however this is only a bandaid on a much larger problem that does not effect young men alone. ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~#penisenvy #femalesexuality #malesexuality #metoo #simonedebeauvoir #cleanyourpenis #jordanpeterson #gender #poststructuralism #queertheory #judithbutler #dick #penis #vagina

a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. he’s the only straight man i’ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text: just in time for the end of the year comes the end of the #vivalavulva project collaboration with @buffetface a series of small hand drawn and collaged artworks of words and phrases highlighting the important power of language and initiating conversations or musings on those themes and left all over london for people to encounter. the last of these pieces were inspired by the @abouttimesnews #payitford campaign to stand in solidarity with dr christine blasey ford’s brave and historic testimonies and all survivors of sexual assault and injustice. even as time passes and we move into a new year it’s important not to forget that the fight for actual justice within the #metoo movement and beyond continues, period poverty continues to affect women and girls the world over and taboos over the language and dialogue of women’s (all kinds of womxn) bodies and autonomy continues to aid in perpetuating systemic oppressions that affect us all. #believesurvivors #ibelievewomen #ibelieveyou #feminism #vivalavulva #buffetface #vagina #periods #languageandpower #letsalllistentoeachother #foundart #collage
